    {
        "content": "<p>I hit a roadblock very early in trying to do anything along these lines, because I can't find the type corresponding to the vector space of smooth functions - if it even exists.</p>\n<p>(One possible option is to use <code>ContMDiffSection</code> and the trivial vector bundle but this feels very obtuse)</p>",
        "id": 538671264,
        "sender_full_name": "Joseph Tooby-Smith",
        "timestamp": 1757515517
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Isn't the most natural space for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Ï</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\rho</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Ï</span></span></span></span> to live in be the space of measures? Probably finite and compactly supported.</p>\n<p>Why do you actually need the space of smooth functions? Shouldn't you just define the inertial tensor for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Ï</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\rho</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Ï</span></span></span></span> be general function/distribution and then in all the theorems require it is compactly supported?</p>",
        "id": 538815989,
        "sender_full_name": "Tomas Skrivan",
        "timestamp": 1757584685
    },
    {
        "content": "<blockquote>\n<p>Isn't the most natural space for  Ï to live in be the space of measures? Probably finite and compactly supported.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I agree this is an option - and would probably work. Though I think distributions are (strictly) more general to work with then measures, in that every measure forms a distribution. Thus, I don't think there is any harm in using distributions, <strong>if</strong> it ends up working. But I would be happy to see it done this way.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Why do you actually need the space of smooth functions? Shouldn't you just define the inertial tensor forÂ <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Ï</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Ï</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Ï</span></span></span></span>Â be general function/distribution and then in all the theorems require it is compactly supported?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Yes this is an option, one could just take distributions <code>ğ“¢(Space, â„) â†’L[â„] â„</code> and enforce the condition that it is compactly supported where necessary. But every such distribution can be extending to a map <code>C^âŠ¤(Space, â„) â†’L[â„] â„ </code>, and it is really this map that we need to define the inertia tensor, because we need to know how it acts on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>k</mi></msub><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>k</mi></msub><msub><mi>Î´</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>âˆ’</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>j</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x_kx_k \\delta_{ij} - x_ix_j</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9805em;vertical-align:-0.2861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3361em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">â€‹</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3361em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">â€‹</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03785em;\">Î´</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3117em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0379em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.05724em;\">ij</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">â€‹</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2861em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">âˆ’</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7167em;vertical-align:-0.2861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3117em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">â€‹</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3117em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.05724em;\">j</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">â€‹</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2861em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>. So I thought it would be easier to just start with compact supported distributions defined directly through <code>C^âŠ¤(Space, â„) â†’L[â„] â„ </code> in the first place. Though maybe I am missing something here.</p>\n<p>What I did manage to do in <a href=\"https://github.com/HEPLean/PhysLean/pull/736\">PhysLean#736</a> is define <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Ï</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\rho</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Ï</span></span></span></span> essentially as <code>C^âŠ¤(Space, â„) â†’â‚—[â„] â„ </code>, which isn't quite right as it needs to be <em>continuous</em> linear  not just linear, but there is no definition of a topology on <code>C^âŠ¤(Space, â„)</code> in Mathlib. I'm also not sure I know where the <em>continuous</em> part would be important in the story.</p>",
